tweet: 7) PARASYMPATHETIC BALANCE #Hugs balance out the nervous system.   #hugme #Love #Happy  pic.twitter.com/zQqSyGXuFD

name: Indiatimes
tweet: 6) STIMULATES SEROTONIN Reaching out and hugging releases endorphins and serotonin into the blood vessels which can cause pleasure and negate pain and sadness and decrease the chances of getting heart problems, helps fight excess weight and prolongs life.   #hugme #Love #Happy  pic.twitter.com/gX0cVaJ2Op

name: Indiatimes
tweet: 5) STIMULATES DOPAMINE Dopamine is responsible for giving us that feel-good feeling, and it’s also responsible for motivation! Hugs stimulate brains to release dopamine, the pleasure hormone.   #hugme #Love #Happy  pic.twitter.com/tM4BX7UExF

name: Indiatimes
tweet: 4) SELF-ESTEEM  Hugging boosts self-esteem, especially in children.   #Amazing #hugme #Love #Happy  pic.twitter.com/0fkwtT0BQV

name: Indiatimes
tweet: 3) PREVENTS DISEASE A hug can boost the growth in premature babies, reduce pain, decrease autoimmune disease symptoms, lowers glucose levels in children with diabetes, and improves immune systems in people with cancer.  #hugme #Love #Happy  pic.twitter.com/7Uf2CDl2qp

name: Indiatimes
tweet: 2) CULTIVATES PATIENCE 👍  By slowing down and taking a moment to offer sincere hugs throughout the day, we’re benefiting ourselves, others, and cultivating better patience within ourselves.  #hugme #Love #Happy  pic.twitter.com/sYmfnBQUUA

name: Indiatimes
tweet: 1) STIMULATES OXYTOCIN When we hug someone, oxytocin is released into our bodies, lowering both our heart rates and our cortisol levels. 👍  Cortisol is the hormone responsible for stress, high blood pressure, and heart disease  #hugme #Love #Happy  pic.twitter.com/4fnnjpeWhb

name: Indiatimes
tweet: “We need 4 hugs a day for survival. We need 8 hugs a day for maintenance. We need 12 hugs a day for growth.” says psychotherapist Virginia Satir 😀😃  If this doesn't make you feel like hugging someone, these reasons will.   #Hug #Love #Happy  pic.twitter.com/gvGJovZhbR

name: Indiatimes
tweet: A longer embrace produces a hormone called "oxytocin", also known as the love hormone that has many benefits in our physical and mental health, helps us, among other things, to relax, to feel safe and calm our fears and anxiety 😀👏 #hugme #Love #Happy  pic.twitter.com/PBPFRaFaMJ
